# Profound Book Club — Project Rules

Website foundation (complete): `docs/e1-website-foundation/website-foundation-summary.md`.

## Init Rules

* Don't add comments that are redundant or obvious. Only add comments that provide meaningful context or explanations.

## Git Rules

* **Trunk-based development (TBD):** Integrate to `main` frequently; pushing to `main` is the normal path. There is **no
  routine PR workflow** — review → commit → push to `main` triggers the stage/prod pipeline (see epic).
* **Local review:** Prefer applying agent work on `main` with a **staged** diff so pre-commit hooks and diffs are easy to
  review. Do **not** create a feature branch for routine story work unless the user explicitly asks for one.
* Never commit or push directly to `main` unless explicitly instructed to do so.
* Never commit or push unless explicitly instructed to do so.
* **Commit workflow:** Always show the proposed commit message and staged changes for review BEFORE executing the commit.
* Wait for explicit approval ("proceed", "commit it", etc.) before running git commit.
* Prefer **segment-sized commits** (~400 added lines max). Run `git diff --staged --stat` before commit; if the diff spans
  multiple checklist layers, split before pushing.

## Delivery & Infrastructure

* **Repos:** `profound-book-club` (app + CDK per environment account); `4ls-org` (AWS Organization OU/accounts, Route 53
  hosted zones, DNS validation and alias records via Terraform).
* **Pipeline:** Modeled on **4ls-site** — Commit → Acceptance (stage) → Production (prod), no manual approval gate. GitHub
  Actions → AWS via **OIDC** (no long-lived keys).
* **dev** is **never** deployed by the pipeline — update dev manually from localhost (CDK). Pipeline handles **stage** and
  **prod** only.
* **Domains:** `dev.profound-book-club.org` / `stage.profound-book-club.org` / `profound-book-club.org`. Apex is
  canonical; `www` 301-redirects to the bare domain.
* **IaC split:** CDK owns app infrastructure (CloudFront, S3 origin, ACM cert request) in each environment account;
  Terraform owns org-level DNS in the `4ls-org` root account.

## Tooling

* Use **PNPM** for dependency management (root and `infrastructure/`).
* Use **TypeScript** from the start so an Astro migration can drop in later without disturbing pipeline or infrastructure.

## Code Style

* Use single quotes for strings consistently
* Limit line length to 120 chars wherever possible
* Include trailing commas in dictionaries and lists
* Avoid redundant comments that simply restate what the code already clearly expresses
* Only add comments when they explain "why" not "what"
* Let the code speak for itself through clear naming and structure

## Documentation Style

* Name markdown documents with all lower case names and kabob-case
* Epic and story docs live under `docs/e*-*/` (e.g. `docs/e1-website-foundation/`)
